			<div class="content" id="post-content-4851278">
									

<p>Placeholder comment, will add in crit in a bit. So far, I like the concept of a non-violent resolution!</p>
<p><strong>Edit:</strong><br />
Line-by-Line:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Show</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>SCP-XXXX-1 is to be stationed with a concierge staffed by a Foundation personnel at all times.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Correct me if I'm wrong, but a concierge is a person, so it should be something like &quot;SCP-XXXX-1 is to be staffed at all times by Foundation personnel, with at least one taking on the role of a concierge.&quot;</p>
<blockquote>
<p>All entrants to SCP-XXXX-1 will allowed one of four choices:</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This doesn't have the best clinical tone, I'd phrase it as &quot;Upon entry, all entrants to SCP-XXXX-1 will be presented with a choice of four objects:&quot;</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The use of amnestics on entrants is punishable by termination.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Crank that way down. Termination means getting killed, usually, and the effects of amnesticization don't seem deserving of punishment via death.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>SCP-XXXX is a symbol visible only to approximately 20% of the population. The reason for this is unknown.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>First, scratch that entire second line. It's an anomaly, of course it's unknown. As for the first sentence, it moves too fast and doesn't give enough information. A symbol? What kind? Visible or invisible in what ways?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>SCP-XXXX’s location varies, however, the most consistent location on which it is found is any type of featureless wall with high amounts of activity and traffic.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>So it moves around? Or is someone drawing it in various places? You gotta explain things more.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Individuals who can see SCP-XXXX are granted access to SCP-XXXX-1; access to SCP-XXXX-1 is done by placing an open hand on SCP-XXXX. The wall on which SCP-XXXX is visible will then dissipate, revealing an entrance to SCP-XXXX-1.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Again, slow down the pacing. It's hard to understand what you mean here, even though you've given enough information.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Clothing themed after the GoI, the Wandsmen.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Hit the brakes. You're introducing an entire new GoI that we know nothing about in a single bullet point, and treating it casually like we're supposed to know everything about them. Also, you'd probably want to state it like &quot;GoI-12345 'The Wandsmen'&quot; or something more clinical.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>How they obtained this information</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&quot;How this information was obtained&quot;</p>
<blockquote>
<p>SCP-XXXX-1’s main retail lobby is managed by PoI-XXXX (need better name later lol) and PoI-XXXX-2, bipedal avian creatures with features similar to owls (Strigiformes) and both standing at approximately 2 meters.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>At this point, these two wouldn't be PoIs. They'd be subanomalies, like SCP-XXXX-2A and SCP-XXXX-2B.</p>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>I'll admit I stopped reading at this point. You very consistently don't give enough information and are lacking clinical tone, to the point where the reader loses interest before they get to the logs. You move along far too quickly to set up any points of reference for the reader, which leads to me being halfway down the article and still feeling lost and confused.</p>
<p>Work on those things, then feel free to message me again to review the full draft.</p>
<p><strong>Edit 2:</strong> Right off the bat, it looks a lot better! The clinical tone has hugely improved, and it's a lot easier to understand what's happening and stay engaged as a result. I read through the entire thing, and the story itself seems pretty decent! The thing I'd recommend you focus on for now is making sure the dialogue sounds natural. One of the best and easiest ways to do that is to simply read it out to yourself, and take note of where the flow is weird.</p>
<p>Excellent job on improving it, guys! Keep at it! I'll let other people give you crit from here, as getting multiple sources of input is important.</p>

							</div>

								
